The '''Rodadero Sea Aquarium and Museum''' is a [[public aquarium]] and [[maritime museum]] located in the ''Inca Inca'' Cove off the Rodadero beach in [[Santa Marta]], [[Colombia]]. It was opened in 1965 by Captain Francisco Ospina Navia<ref name="acopazoa">{{cite web|title=Acuario Rodadero|url=http://www.acopazoa.org/esp/miembro.php?id=9|language=Spanish|accessdate=2009-12-16|publisher=Colombian Zoo and Aquarium Association}}</ref>. The aquarium is part of the National Network of Museums of Colombia<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.museoscolombianos.gov.co/inbox/files/docs/d1magdalena.pdf|format=pdf|language=Spanish|publisher=Red Nacional de Museos|accessdate-2009-12-16|date=2009-07-15|title=Directorio de museos del Magdalena|trans_title=Directory of museums of Magdalena}}</ref> and part of ''ACOPAZOA'', the Colombian branch of the [[World Association of Zoos and Aquariums]]<ref name="acopazoaen"/>. Accessible mainly by [[motorboat]], the aquarium has 13 pools with direct connection to the [[Caribbean Sea]], and 15 glass [[aquaria]] that contain over 805 animals that include [[sharks]], [[sea turtles]], [[dolphins]], [[sea lions]], [[crustaceans]], [[fishes]] and [[seabirds]], 98% of which are [[Indigenous (ecology)|native to the area]]<ref name="acopazoa"/>.

The Aquarium also contains a museum section that exhibits dissected specimens and nautical equipment, as well as an exhibition that focuses on the pre-columbine culture of the [[Tairona]]s and their connection to the sea<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.acuariorodadero.com/acerca-de/|language=Spanish|accessdate=2009-12-16|title=Patrimonio Tur<U+00ED>stico|date=2008-03-13|publisher=Rodadero Sea Aquarium and Museum}}</ref>.

